Node.Notes: Uncertain. Either "shoot" (i.e., new plant sprout) or "rod."
""Arrogance," but many correct word slightly to yield "back." Perhaps best to leave text unchanged and translate as something like "A shoot of pride [is] in the mouth of the fool.""
Uncertain whether "fools" is subject (mismatch with verb). "Guilt offering" (maybe "guilt" instead?) could be subject. But something like "fools scoff at a guilt offering" probably best.
Uncertain what "a good man [will be satisfied] from upon him" means. Some change text to read "from his deeds." Perhaps something like "the good man [will be satisfied] more than him"?
Many change "folly" to "garland" because of the tautology. However, best to keep text and sense may be that fools do not change, folly remains folly.
Many change the text slightly to read "integrity." If "death" correct, may be an expression of belief in personal immortality.

Many wonder how wisdom can be known among fools. Some insert "not" on basis of LXX. Some suggest turning statement into a question. Probably best to have something like "[even] among fools she is known."
Most make sense of this as L: carried over from first half "upon one who brings shame."
